response.name: Footer API
response.body:
{
    "id": 1,
    "footer_title": "About Heritage Gallery",
    "footer_description": "In 1937, Ghanshyam Das Birla, who had started out at the Pathashala as a child, implemented the Wardha Scheme of Education in Pilani. During World War II, the Birla Education Trust responded to the government's request and established a centre at Pilani to train technicians for the Royal Indian Navy. In 1943, the primary school was converted into a civilian naval centre, which eventually evolved into the Birla Engineering College in 1946.\r\n\r\nThe college started offering degree and post-graduate courses in Mathematics, Physics, Chemistry, Zoology, and Botany, and facilities were provided for advanced research leading to doctorates in these subjects. The first batch of Mechanical and Electrical engineering students passed their Final B.E. degree examinations in 1950. In 1952, Birla College was bifurcated into two independent colleges: Birla Institute of Technology & Science (BITS) and Birla College of Science. BITS Pilani has since become one of the premier engineering institutes in India.",

}
